title: New Taliban Chancellor Bars Women From Kabul University
content: The new policy for Afghanistan’s premier university is another major blow to women’s rights under Taliban rule, and to a two-decade effort to build up higher education.

title: Why Haitians in Chile Keep Heading North to the U.S.
content: Many of the Haitian migrants who recently entered Texas had taken refuge for years in Chile. Some said they faced increasing joblessness, poverty and hostility there.

title: As Gas Stations Run Dry, Britons Cope With Disruptions to Daily Life
content: Getting to work, driving a taxi, making an ambulance run: Fuel shortages and long lines at gas stations have Britons scrambling to make trips they once took for granted.

title: Australia Took On China. Did It Get It Right?
content: The country is wrestling with the political and economic consequences of its sharp turn in policy and tone — including an erosion of tolerance.

title: China’s Vow to Reduce Abortions Sparks Public Worries
content: The short mention in a sweeping health plan lacked specifics, but it set off concerns in a country with a history of intrusive reproductive policies.

title: The Social Democrats won narrowly, their first victory since 2002.
content: Chancellor Angela Merkel’s Christian Democrats suffered a dramatic defeat in Sunday’s elections.

title: Power Outages Hit China, Threatening the Economy and Christmas
content: High demand and soaring energy prices have forced some factories to shut down, adding further problems for already snarled global supply chains.

title: As Tunisia’s President Cements One-Man Rule, Opposition Grows
content: In his latest step to consolidate power, President Kais Saied set up a system under which he will essentially govern the country by decree, bypassing the Constitution.

title: Catalan Separatist Leaves Italy, Dodging Spain’s Latest Effort to Prosecute Him
content: After briefly holding Carles Puigdemont on a Spanish arrest warrant, Italian authorities released him, and he left the country on Monday.

title: Labour’s Leader Struggles to Emerge From Boris Johnson’s Shadow
content: Competent but low on charisma, Keir Starmer has yet to give British voters a clear reason to support the main opposition party, critics say.

title: How China Plans to Avert an Evergrande Financial Crisis
content: Control of the banking system gives Beijing the tools to stop a broader collapse, officials believe, while censorship and police powers can stifle protests.

title: Five Years After Peace Deal, Colombia Is Running Out of Time, Experts Say
content: A treaty with rebels in 2016 called for the end of a decades-long war. But that is not the same as achieving peace, and the window for doing so may be closing.

title: Women Enslaved by ISIS Say They Did Not Consent to a Film About Them
content: The acclaimed documentary “Sabaya” portrays the rescue of Yazidi women sexually enslaved by the Islamic State terrorist group. But many of the traumatized women said they never agreed to be in the film.

title: It’s Never Too Late to Publish a Debut Book and Score a Netflix Deal
content: Jocelyn Nicole Johnson, at 50, is not the average age of a debut author. But the public school teacher describes herself as a “literary debutante” with the October publication of “My Monticello.”

title: Your Tuesday Briefing
content: The race to form Germany’s next government.

title: Canada Doubles Its Afghan Refugee Resettlement Target to 40,000 People
content: The official announcement was made by Canada’s foreign minister on Monday evening, speaking at the United Nations General Assembly.

title: Bolsonaro’s wife was vaccinated during their visit to New York for the U.N.G.A.
content: The president of Brazil began his visit by defying a U.N. honor system requiring proof of vaccination, and four members of his entourage have tested positive.

title: North Korea Launches Short-Range Missile as Country’s Envoy Speaks at U.N.
content: The launch came just three days after the sister of North Korea’s leader, Kim Jong-un, said the country would consider holding a meeting with the South and declaring an official end to the Korean War.

title: American Siblings Barred From Leaving China for 3 Years Return to U.S.
content: Their release coincided with an agreement on Friday that cleared the way for a senior executive of Huawei Technologies, the Chinese telecommunications giant, to return to China.

title: Winner but Not Chancellor, Yet: The Race to Replace Merkel
content: Olaf Scholz, the leader of the center-left Social Democrats, narrowly won the night. But now the hard part begins — building a durable governing coalition.

title: Maps show where Merkel’s party lost ground: everywhere.
content: The conservatives who have been the dominant force in modern German politics suffered their worst defeat, while the Social Democrats and Greens made gains.

title: Your Tuesday Briefing
content: Germany’s election results.

title: Two transgender women win seats in the next German Parliament.
content: The two lawmakers, both from the Green Party, reflect the growing visibility and acceptance of transgender people, who have never before held seats in the Parliament.

title: Intelligence Agencies Pushed to Use More Commercial Satellites
content: Congress wants the government to turn to the private sector to augment the capabilities of highly classified spy satellites.

title: Why Britain Is Embracing Pounds and Ounces
content: Britain is planning a future that relies on greater usage of its imperial system of weights and measurements. Here’s why it’s happening now.

title: Red Covid
content: Covid’s partisan pattern is growing more extreme.

title: Sydney plans to start leaving its lockdown in October.
content: A phased reopening of Australia’s largest city is tied to reaching a series of milestones in vaccination rates.

title: Intimate Portraits of Mexico’s Third-Gender Muxes
content: On the Isthmus of Tehuantepec in southern Mexico, a community of the local Zapotec people has long accepted — and celebrated — gender nonconformity.

title: ‘Every Day Is Frightening’: Working for the Top U.S. Employer Amid Covid
content: As offices debate the merits and logistics of reopening, a parallel sphere of workers like Peter Naughton, a Walmart cashier, seem to inhabit another world. Often their jobs just got really hard.

title: N.Y.’s governor urges health care workers to ‘do the right thing’ and get shots.
content: “It’s not a role I relish,” Gov. Kathy C. Hochul said. “But I also realistically know that there are people who will not come back to their jobs.”

title: Vowing to modernize industry and ‘halt man-made climate change,’ Olaf Scholz claims a mandate.
content: The Social Democrats made significant gains on Sunday’s election but will need to find coalition partners to form a government.

title: Your Monday Briefing
content: A narrow victory for the Social Democrats.

title: German Election Heralds Messier Politics and Weaker Leadership After Merkel
content: Preliminary results indicated an outcome so tight that it could take months of talks to form a new government at a critical moment for Europe.

title: Your Monday Briefing
content: Germany’s election is neck and neck.

title: As Covid wave pushes up demand, Costco limits purchases of toilet paper and water.
content: The retailer cited an uptick in demand because of the Delta variant and a shortage of truck drivers.
